"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99894","Home Office","false","2014-10-24","<p>Police recorded crime in Harlow Community Safety Partnership has fallen by 11% since June 2010.<br><br>The Government’s police reforms, including cutting unnecessary targets and red tape and giving officers the discretion to use their professional judgment, mean that forces can focus on cutting crime. We have also introduced direct democratic accountability through Police and Crime Commissioners, ensuring that the police focus on tackling the crimes that matter to local people.</p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-10-24T15:02:15.9473764Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99894/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99894/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99894/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Crime: Harlow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of crime levels in Harlow; and what steps she is taking to reduce such levels.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","211030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99895","Home Office","false","2014-10-24","<p>The data requested are given in the table. Data for Harlow are available from 2002/03.<br><br>The Office for National Statistics publishes quarterly statistics on crime. As part of this, a set of open data tables are published, showing crime at Police Force Area and Community Safety Partnership level. These contain the data requested, and can be found using this link:<br><br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-10-24T14:58:27.2197522Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99895/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99895/answer","PQ 211031 - table.xls","Police recorded crime in Harlow","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99895/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Crime: Harlow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many crimes of each type have been committed in Harlow constituency in each of the last 15 years.","false","Biography information for Robert Halfon","Harlow","Robert Halfon","211031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99896","Home Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Home Office did not have an automated system to record the number of foreign national offenders (FNOs) before 2006. As a result we are unable to provide data for the number of FNOs who were removed between 2000 and 2006. Since 2010, this Government has removed 22,000 FNOs. <br><br>The Immigration Act 2014 will have a significant impact on the ability of FNOs to delay removal by mounting legal challenges whilst in the UK. We have reduced the number of appeal rights for foreign criminals from 17 to 4, and set out clearly in primary legislation the right balance on the right to a family life under Article 8 of the European Convention on Human Rights to prevent individuals from playing the system. This means that appeals can only be brought where the Home Office has refused a protection (asylum or humanitarian protection) claim, a human rights claim or a claim based on EU free movement rights.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-10T16:30:31.9332568Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99896/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99896/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99896/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99896/answer/previousversion/23870","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Prisoners: Repatriation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many foreign national prisoners were removed from the UK in each year between 2000 and 2006.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","211023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99897","Home Office","false","2014-10-28","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-10-28T14:20:05.8224837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99897/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99897/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99897/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Telecommunications: Court Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many production orders to access stored electronic communications have been invoked by each UK police force in each year since May 2010; and what the prosecution rate is following the invoking of such production orders.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","211013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99898","Home Office","false","2014-10-27","<p>The following detections of clandestine migrants have been made across all UK sea ports since 2011 (to obtain data pre-2011 would be at disproportionate cost): 692 detections in 2011, 568 in 2012 and 678 in 2013. <br><br>In order to ensure the integrity and security of the UK border, Her Majesty’s Government does not comment on port specific statistics.<br><br>The figures quoted are management information, subject to internal quality checks and may be subject to change. The figures include those detected at a sea port and on ferries.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-10-27T12:16:26.0690949Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99898/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99898/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99898/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Illegal Immigrants: Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many clandestine migrants have been identified at (a) the UK's seaport and (b) the Port of Tilbury in each year since 2000.","false","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","211063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99899","Home Office","false","2014-10-23","<p>On 7 July the Home Secretary announced to the House that she had appointed Peter Wanless to lead a Review of an investigation by an independent expert into what information the Home Office had received in relation to child abuse allegations during the period 1979 and 1999. The Permanent Secretary appointed Richard Whittam QC to assist in this task. The Review has had access to all material identified which would relate to child abuse and which the Department still holds. The Home Secretary has now received the report of the Review and is considering its findings ahead of the full report being published.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-10-23T16:10:00.349232Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99899/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99899/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99899/answer","Lewes","Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99899/answer/previousversion/23874","Biography information for Norman Baker","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether any meetings took place in her Department between 1980 and 1985 to discuss the alleged involvement of hon. Members in child abuse; and whether minutes of such meetings were given to the then Secretary of State.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","211094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99900","Home Office","false","2014-10-23","<p>On 7 July the Home Secretary announced to the House that she had appointed Peter Wanless to lead a Review of an investigation by an independent expert into what information the Home Office had received in relation to child abuse allegations during the period 1979 and 1999.</p><p>The Permanent Secretary appointed Richard Whittam QC to assist in this task. The Review has had access to all material identified which would relate to child abuse and which the Department still holds. The Home Secretary has now received the report of the Review and is considering its findings ahead of the full report being published.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-10-23T16:18:17.1714451Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99900/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99900/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99900/answer","Lewes","Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99900/answer/previousversion/23878","Biography information for Norman Baker","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether files relating to investigations by her Department of hon. Members and allegations of child abuse between 1980 and 1985 have been made available to the Wanless Review.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","211096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99901","Home Office","false","2014-10-24","<p>The Home Department policy is that a fee must be paid prior to the application receiving immigration consideration. An application will only go forward for immigration consideration if it is valid. <br><br>For an immigration application to be valid a number of requirements must be met. These include the payment of the application fee, unless the applicant satisfies the criteria for a fee exemption. Where an application is invalid and cannot be processed the application fee is returned to the applicant.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-10-24T14:55:07.3746503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99901/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99901/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99901/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department's policy is on collecting fees for visa applications in advance of the application being processed.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","211067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99902","Home Office","false","2014-10-23","<p>On 7 July the Home Secretary announced to the House that she had appointed Peter Wanless to lead a Review of an investigation by an independent expert into what information the Home Office had received in relation to child abuse allegations during the period 1979 and 1999.</p><p>The Permanent Secretary appointed Richard Whittam QC to assist in this task. The Review has had access to all material identified which would relate to child abuse and which the Department still holds. The Home Secretary has now received the report of the Review and is considering its findings ahead of the full report being published.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Lewes","Norman Baker",,"2014-10-23T16:16:05.3612436Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99902/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99902/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99902/answer","Lewes","Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99902/answer/previousversion/23876","Biography information for Norman Baker","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether any files were taken from the journalist Don Hale, editor of the Bury Messenger in the 1980s; who authorised the seizure of such files; and whether the material seized included minutes of investigations within the Home Office concerning child abuse and hon. Members.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","211095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99903","Home Office","false","2014-10-23","<p>Home Office Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of partners, as well as organisations and individuals in the public and private sectors, as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of ministerial meetings are passed to the Cabinet Office on a quarterly basis and are subsequently published on the Gov.uk website: <a href="http://data.gov.uk/dataset/ministerial-data-home-office" target="_blank">http://data.gov.uk/dataset/ministerial-data-home-office</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-10-23T14:54:12.6393768Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99903/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99903/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99903/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Rape","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she last met the (a) Chief Constable of Cheshire and (b) the Police and Crime Commissioner to discuss HM Inspector of Constabulary's finding on the recording of rape crimes; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","211055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99904","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-23","<p>The UK implements all sanctions agreed at the UN. These sanctions are implemented via the EU. The UK is responsible for implementation for the Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies. The US has its own domestic legislation by which it can introduce sanctions. This is an entirely separate process to the UN. The UK would not implement US domestic sanctions, although there may be individuals that the US designates which are also listed under UN sanctions.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-10-23T13:13:13.6749629Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99904/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99904/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99904/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-20","Sanctions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, for what reasons the UK has not applied sanctions to all individuals on the US and UN sanction lists.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","211104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99905","Home Office","false","2014-10-24","<p>We refer to our answer to PQ 210481 and did not provide details of visits by Ministers to Torbay constituency because as was the case with previous administrations, it is not the Government's practice to provide details of all such meetings.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-10-24T16:03:05.9408502Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99905/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99905/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99905/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99905/answer/previousversion/23924","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-20","Torbay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 17 October 2014 to Question 210481, for what reasons her Answer did not provide details of visits by Ministers to Torbay constituency.","false","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","211133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99906","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-27","<p>Since May 2010, DFID Sierra Leone has supported the distribution of 2.3 million long lasting insecticide treated bed nets (LLINs) through two nationwide campaigns completed in June 2011 and May 2014. The aim of these campaigns was to achieve universal coverage of LLINs in Sierra Leone as the most effective means of preventing malaria. A rapid assessment following the 2014 distribution campaign found that 81% of households visited nationwide were using at least one mosquito net, up from 37% in 2008. However, an evaluation designed to assess the longer term effectiveness of the campaign has been postponed due to the Ebola crisis. In addition, the Global Fund has provided a further 600,000 nets.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-10-27T17:17:31.941274Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99906/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99906/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99906/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-20","Sierra Leone","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assistance her Department has provided to Sierra Leone to combat malaria in each year since May 2010; and what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of the malaria prevention programme in that country.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","211089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99907","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-27","<p>The Department has not, to date, received any reports.</p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-10-27T17:16:23.1316518Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99907/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99907/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99907/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-20","Ghana","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what reports she has received of the potential effects of the Plant Breeders Bill in Ghana on small-scale farmers in that country.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","211018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99908","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-23","<p>The Development Tracker was launched by the Secretary of State on 31 October 2013 to present project documents, budgets, transactions and locations of DFID projects in line with the International Aid Transparency Initiative (IATI) open data standard. The Tracker has enabled a step change in public access to information on how UK development assistance is being used.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Tracker is continually assessed and improved according to user need. The Tracker has 14000 visits and 80000 page views per month. There are 2442 email subscribers and 12949 email alerts were delivered in October 2014. Almost 60% of users are from the UK, with a wide range of users from countries where we work.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Tracker has received positive feedback from users. In October 2014, DFID was ranked 2nd in the global Publish What You Fund Aid Transparency Index which noted that the Tracker represents “a major step forward in improving the accessibility of information on UK development assistance by integrating IATI data for NGO implementing partners with its own data and that of other UK government departments”.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-10-23T16:44:36.4328344Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99908/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99908/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99908/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-20","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Development Tracker; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","211151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99909","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-10-23","<p>In February 2014 the UK Government hosted a major conference of global leaders to help eradicate the illegal wildlife trade and better protect the world’s most iconic species, such as rhinos, from the threat of extinction.</p><p><br> Over 40 nations attended. The result was the London Conference Declaration, containing 25 commitments to action on enforcement and criminal justice, demand reduction and sustainable livelihoods. The UK is actively supporting Botswana in hosting a further Conference to review progress in March 2015.</p><p><br>The UK chairs the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) Rhino Working Group. This brings together countries implicated in the illegal trade in rhino horn, whether as a range or a consumer state, to share information and to develop and implement demand reduction strategies to help protect the rhino. The Group met and reported during the 65<sup>th</sup> CITES Standing Committee meeting in July 2014 and will do so again at the 66<sup>th</sup> meeting in January 2016.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-10-23T14:15:32.0106972Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99909/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99909/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99909/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-20","Rhinoceros: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will hold discussions at an international level on urgent action to prevent the extinction of northern white rhinos.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","211179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99910","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-23","<p>DFID does not record information on the classifications of business below the overall category ‘small and medium-sized enterprises’ (SME’s) therefore we cannot respond to the level of detail you have specified.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","211175","2014-10-23T16:45:45.7503337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99910/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99910/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/99910/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-20","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of her Department's (a) direct and (b) indirect spending on procurement was with companies defined as micro businesses according to the definition given by the Annex to the European Commission Recommendation 2003/361/EC of 6 May 2003 for each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","211174"
