"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93850","Home Office","false","2014-10-22","<p>The UK has some of the toughest gun laws in the world. The Coalition Government is of the view that controls on firearms should be targeted fairly and <br>proportionately, striking the right balance between securing public safety without unnecessarily affecting legitimate users. <br><br>The licensing of firearms and shotguns is carried out by the police and the assessment of the suitability of an individual to possess a firearm or shotgun <br>is an operational matter. Forces must have appropriate measures in place to ensure that all relevant information and intelligence is readily available for <br>the assessment of suitability to be made on a continuous basis.</p><p />","Lewes","Norman Baker","210868 ; 210869","2014-10-22T17:05:42.0966408Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93850/answer","Biography information for Norman Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93850/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-16","Terrorism: Firearms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate her Department has made of how many shotgun certificate or firearms licence holders are vulnerable to (a) criminal or terrorist activities and (b) approaches by those engaged in criminal or terrorist activity; and if she will place in the Library a copy of any risk assessment undertaken on this matter.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","210870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93851","Home Office","false","2014-10-22","<p>Egmont Group members share financial intelligence through a dedicated secure network. Egmont Group membership consists of approximately 147 countries and jurisdictions and is underpinned by the principles of the Egmont Charter to which members are signatories. The service enables secure transmission of messages together with attachments and is email based.</p><p>FIU.Net is a European Union initiative which is available to the National Financial Intelligence Units of all EU Member States. FIU.Net provides a secure method of requesting and sharing financial intelligence between Member States. FIU.Net allows for transmission of messages together with attachments via dedicated secure servers in each jurisdiction. FIU.Net provides UK law enforcement agencies with additional functionality over Egmont secure web, such as anonymised case and data matching.</p><p>The UK’s domestic legislation allows for the exchange of intelligence data with overseas partners. Council Decision 2000/642/JHA provides a gateway for those member states, in the absence of specific domestic gateway legislation, to exchange data lawfully and efficiently. As a signatory to the decision the UK is able to exchange relevant information with countries lacking domestic gateway legislation.</p><p>If we ceased to be bound by the Framework Decision we may lose access to FIU.net. Further, we would no longer benefit from the deadlines for prompt exchange of information provided by the 'Swedish Initiative' (FD 2006/960/JHA) in conjunction with FD 2000/642/JHA.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-10-22T16:45:53.2788217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93851/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93851/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93851/answer/previousversion/23258","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-16","Egmont Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, through what secure means financial intelligence units of Egmont Group members exchange information; and how that means of exchange differs from information exchange through FIU.net.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Jacob Rees-Mogg","210934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93852","Home Office","false","2014-10-24","<p>Council Decision 2007/533/JHA is legislative basis for governing the second generation of the Schengen Information System (SIS II) for the purposes of police and judicial co-operation in criminal matters. <br><br>In line with Article 25(2) of Council Decision 2007/533/JHA, the National Crime Agency has the authority to refuse to validate Article 26 alerts on <br>proportionality grounds where a general instruction has been issued. This means that UK police officers will not arrest people subject to an Article 26 alert where there is a lack of proportionality.<br><br>Concerning Article 34 alerts, under Article 35 the UK authorities are not required actively to ascertain the place of residence or domicile of relevant persons, only to communicate such information. Clearly, if they do not hold such information it cannot be communicated. However, if there is supporting information that justifies activity to ascertain proactively the place of residence or domicile of relevant persons action will be taken by UK authorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-10-24T16:07:30.118443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93852/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93852/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93852/answer/previousversion/23255","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-16","Schengen Agreement: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 2 September 2014, to Question 207060, on what grounds the Government considers that Article 34 alerts from other EU Member States under Council Decision 2007/533/JHA will not require UK authorities actively to ascertain and communicate the place of residence or domicile of the relevant persons, given the provision of Article 35 of that Decision.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Jacob Rees-Mogg","210935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93853","Home Office","false","2014-10-24","<p>Egmont Group members share financial intelligence through a dedicated secure network. Egmont Group membership consists of approximately 147 countries and jurisdictions and is underpinned by the principles of the Egmont Charter to which members are signatories. The service enables secure transmission of messages together with attachments and is email based.</p><p>FIU.Net is a European Union initiative which is available to the National Financial Intelligence Units of all EU Member States. FIU.Net provides a secure method of requesting and sharing financial intelligence between Member States. FIU.Net allows for transmission of messages together with attachments via dedicated secure servers in each jurisdiction. FIU.Net provides UK law enforcement agencies with additional functionality over Egmont secure web, such as anonymised case and data matching.</p><p>The UK’s domestic legislation allows for the exchange of intelligence data with overseas partners. Council Decision 2000/642/JHA provides a gateway for those member states, in the absence of specific domestic gateway legislation, to exchange data lawfully and efficiently. As a signatory to the decision the UK is able to exchange relevant information with countries lacking domestic gateway legislation.</p><p>If we ceased to be bound by the Framework Decision we may lose access to FIU.net. Further, we would no longer benefit from the deadlines for prompt exchange of information provided by the 'Swedish Initiative' (FD 2006/960/JHA) in conjunction with FD 2000/642/JHA.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-10-24T16:05:30.2164462Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93853/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93853/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93853/answer/previousversion/23254","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-16","Egmont Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 2 September 2014, to Question 207074, what specific benefits Council Decision 2000/642/JHA provides for exchanging financial intelligence in addition to Egmont Group membership.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Jacob Rees-Mogg","210936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93854","Home Office","false","2014-10-22","<p>Council Decision 2007/533/JHA is legislative basis for governing the second generation of the Schengen Information System (SIS II) for the purposes of police and judicial co-operation in criminal matters. <br><br>In line with Article 25(2) of Council Decision 2007/533/JHA, the National Crime Agency has the authority to refuse to validate Article 26 alerts on <br>proportionality grounds where a general instruction has been issued. This means that UK police officers will not arrest people subject to an Article 26 alert where there is a lack of proportionality.<br><br>Concerning Article 34 alerts, under Article 35 the UK authorities are not required actively to ascertain the place of residence or domicile of relevant persons, only to communicate such information. Clearly, if they do not hold such information it cannot be communicated. However, if there is supporting information that justifies activity to ascertain proactively the place of residence or domicile of relevant persons action will be taken by UK authorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-10-22T16:46:43.7479343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93854/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93854/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93854/answer/previousversion/23260","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-16","Schengen Agreement: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 2 September 2014, to Question 207060, whether UK police would be able to avoid arresting persons pursuant to an Article 26 alert under Council Decision 2007/533/JHA on grounds of lack of proportionality, should the UK connect to the Schengen Information System II, given the provisions of Article 25 of that Decision requiring a decision not to arrest to be taken by a judicial authority.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Jacob Rees-Mogg","210932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93855","Home Office","false","2014-10-23","<p>It is a matter for Member States to define how their competent authorities establish joint investigation teams. However, the Second Additional Protocol is not in force in Austria, Cyprus, Germany, Greece, Hungary, Italy, Luxembourg and Spain and as such does not offer a basis for the UK to establish joint investigation teams with those Member States. To date the UK has participated in 54 joint investigation teams.</p><p>This includes six JITs with Member States that have not ratified the Second Additional Protocol, five of which are ongoing. A recent example of a Joint Investigation Team was Operation Birkhill, which was a joint operation with Hungary targeting a UK-Hungarian sex trafficking organised crime group. As a result of the operation, five people were sentenced to a total of 36 years imprisonment earlier this year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-10-23T15:13:29.8578962Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93855/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93855/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93855/answer/previousversion/23259","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-16","Schengen Agreement: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of whether Framework Decision 2002/465/JHA would permit national legislation that required the relevant competent authorities to establish joint investigation teams under the Second Additional Protocol to the European Convention on Mutual Assistance in Criminal Matters, where that Protocol is available, rather than under the Framework Decision.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Jacob Rees-Mogg","210933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93856","Home Office","false","2014-10-24","<p>Border Force officers assess travellers for symptoms of Ebola following standard protocols issued by Public Health England that have been in place at all ports, including Dover, since August 2014. <br><br>Enhanced screening for Ebola at specific ports has begun, in line with advice from the Chief Medical Officer, focusing initially on Heathrow, Gatwick, St Pancras, Manchester and Birmingham. This is being carried out by Public Health England. <br><br>Border Force regularly liaises with the relevant French authorities regarding all operational matters at the port of Calais.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-10-24T17:21:41.929593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93856/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93856/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93856/answer/previousversion/23262","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-16","Ebola: Dover Port","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department plans to take to screen arrivals from West Africa via Europe at the Port of Dover for Ebola; and what steps her Department is taking to liaise with the French authorities to facilitate the screening of people temporarily resident in Calais while seeking to enter the UK illegally for Ebola.","false","Biography information for Sir Roger Gale","North Thanet","Sir Roger Gale","210916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93857","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-21","<p /> <p>Legal aid for personal injury claims including mesothelioma was withdrawn by the last Government in April 2000 as conditional fee agreements (CFAs) were available. This Government has since reformed the way in which CFAs operate, but its decision to apply those reforms to mesothelioma cases was recently overturned by the High Court. The Government is considering the way forward in the light of that judgment.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-10-21T16:05:44.5141457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93857/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93857/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-16","Mesothelioma: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the decision by the High Court that the Government's proposals for legal aid involving mesothelioma proceedings were not lawfully made, what plans the Government has to initiate a further review.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Mr Andy Slaughter","210956"
